default7.0 default              defaultImpact on Adult Social Care Services Following the 2010 Spending Reviewdefault&#xa0;
default7.1
default              
defaultScrutiny in five local authorities responded that Committees had received evidence on the impact on the provision of adult social care following the 2010 spending review settlement and the ability of local authorities to make the necessary savings. Examples of the issues considered by the Committees are:
default&#xa0;
default
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFairer charging and eligibility criteria
default
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFinancial pressure on Adult services which may result in the local authority raising the threshold for local authority funded care to critical
default
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe funding for Adult Social Care must be seen in the context of the overall reduction in funding for local government and that efficiency savings in the NHS can result in additional costs for the local authority
default
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultImplication of the Care and Support Bill
default
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultEvidence in performance and Local Account reports
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default              
defaultTelford and Wrekin Council Scrutiny
defaultThe Budget and Finance Scrutiny Committee in Telford and Wrekin has monitored the financial pressures on the Adult Care budget following the 2010 Spending Review. In addition to this, as part of the Health and Adult Care Scrutiny Committee’s review of Continuing Health Care members received evidence that the average reduction in funding for Local Government was initially 27%, but following later announcements this increased to 33%.   A detailed report will be considered by the Health and Adult Care Scrutiny Committee and members of the Budget and Finance Scrutiny Committee on the 4
defaultth
default November 2013.This sets out the pressures on the Council’s Adult Care budget which accounts for 36% of the Council’s spend and over 80% of this is spent directly on providing care. The Adult Social Care budget has been reduced by £7million which has been achieved through efficiencies, new ways of working and staff reductions.  The Adult Care budget is expected to find a further £6.5 million to achieve the savings required by 2015/16 while there continues to be an underlying growth in the number of people needing services compared with the number of people leaving the service. The Scrutiny Committee will consider the financial improvement plan put in place to manage the Adult Care Services budget.
default&#xa0;
